Description: Fix CVE-2026-41292 - Cap EDNS option parsing to prevent CPU DoS
 Parsing a long list of incoming EDNS options degrades performance because
 the option-parsing loops in parse_edns_options_from_query() and
 parse_extract_edns_from_response_msg() are unbounded. A remote attacker
 can send DNS messages packed with many EDNS options (e.g., thousands of
 zero-length options inside one OPT RR) to exhaust CPU on worker threads.
 .
 This patch caps the parsing loops at MAX_PARSED_EDNS_OPTIONS = 100,
 mirroring the upstream fix. Backported to 1.17.1 (Debian 12) by hand
 because the function signatures of parse_edns_options_from_query drifted
 between 1.17.1 and 1.25.1; the four mechanical edits (macro, counter,
 loop-guard, increment) are applied to the same vulnerable loops.
Origin: backport, https://github.com/NLnetLabs/unbound/commit/ef5ca84360934fa1e857ebc371d4b093aea6355d
Author: W.C.A. Wijngaards <wouter@nlnetlabs.nl>
Last-Update: 2026-06-03

